poem:
Oscilloscope Lissajous Bloom

In ohmic gloam the benches loom,
and solder-pop goes fizz and plume;
The lab-winds hush in phosphor gloom,
to watch an oscilloscope lissajous bloom.

"Beware the Lissajous-Bloom, my kit,
the jitter-gnash, the phase-gnawed spume;
Beware the alias-elf that flit,
and mind the ringy-rattle-boom!"

He grabbed his 10x probe of light,
and tuned the sweep in copper tune;
He zeroed ground and trigged just right,
to net its crossings soon as noon.

He lingered where the bus-bars brood,
beside the dum-dum grounding broom;
His knuckles hummed with solder-mood,
beneath the scope's cathedral gloom.

Then swishing through the sine-swept air,
a crossy-curvet twist of doom;
Its looplings lipped a phosphor glare—
the hisssome Lissajous Bloom!

Zing-zap! the probing phaseblade flew;
the trace went clitter-clatter-boom;
He sliced the crossings clean in two
and cleft the Lissajous Bloom.

It sputtered with a squelchy spume,
uncurled its knots to measured doom;
He looped the loop into a loom,
and bore it blinking through the room.

"O measure-mirth!" the elder cried;
He capered 'round the faucets' boom;
"Thou trimmed the tangle-crossing tide!"
"Ho-hah!" they chimed about the room.

And ohmic night reclocks the room;
the bench-lamps purr with amber plume;
Yet somewhere sings in slumbered gloom
an oscilloscope Lissajous bloom.
